Runner beans and sweet peas - have them clamber over tepee structures, and enjoy not only their productive side but also the lovely flowers and tendrils. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bc/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet12.jpg/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet12.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bc/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet12.jpg/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet12.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Beets. Some varieties have dark green leaves and dark red stems. Beet greens can also be used as salad greens. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet13.jpg/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet13.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/76/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet13.jpg/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-2Bullet13.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Because of the seasonal, temporary nature of most vegetables, you will probably want certain elements to anchor your garden when nothing is growing, or when plants are very small. Here are some elements that can help create permanent structure:

Raised beds may be created in a variety of shapes, heights, and patterns. Remember that you will want easy access to the contents of vegetable beds for weeding and harvesting. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/08\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/08\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Paths, patios, and lawns surrounding the vegetable garden are important elements of negative space. Correctly planned, paths also give you access to your garden without stepping in cultivated areas. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a1\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a1\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Trellises give your vegetables somewhere to climb, but they probably also persist in your garden during the off-season. Make them attractive, by themselves. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d9\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d9\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Permanent plantings. These may be trees (fruit trees or ornamental), perennial herbs or vegetables, or simply ornamental perennials. Whatever permanent plantings you choose, try to situate them so that they do not compete too much with your vegetables for light, water, or soil. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/14\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/14\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Fences, hedges and walls create a perimeter for the garden and they add color and structure. They may also support climbing vines, trellises, or espaliered fruit trees{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d3\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet5.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/d\/d3\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet5.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Garden statuary, fountains, sundials, and other ornaments are often placed at the center of a formal garden layout. Include one or two to create interest, but don't overdo it. After all, you're growing vegetables, not statuary. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6a\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet6.jpg\/v4-460px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6a\/Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet6.jpg\/v4-760px-Grow-a-Decorative-Vegetable-Garden-Step-7Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
